.TH TIMBERFS-RECORDS 5 "2026-07-12" "timberfs" "File Formats"
.SH NAME
timberfs-records \- typed, NUL-framed log-entry record stream
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B timberfs query \-\-records
.I ...
| consumer
.SH DESCRIPTION
The record stream is the pipe interface between timberfs selection
(\fBtimberfs query\fR) and entry-aware consumers. It carries whole log
ENTRIES (a stamped line plus its continuation lines) as verbatim bytes,
interleaved with typed metadata records. It is a byte stream, not a
text format: read it with a parser, not with line-oriented tools (for
those, use
.B \-0
\(em bare NUL-terminated entries \(em or plain text).
.SH GRAMMAR
.nf
.RS
stream  := record*
record  := body NUL
body    := RS kind (US key=value)*    metadata record
         | payload                    entry payload, verbatim bytes
.RE
.fi
.PP
.B RS
is byte 0x1E (ASCII record separator),
.B US
is 0x1F (unit separator),
.B NUL
is 0x00. A record whose first byte is RS is metadata; every other
record is the verbatim payload of the entry announced by the
immediately preceding
.B entry
metadata record. Keys never contain \(lq=\(rq; the first \(lq=\(rq
splits key from value. Values never contain NUL or US (timberfs
refuses to emit such a stream). Payload bytes are arbitrary \(em
including NUL: the
.B len
field of the
.B entry
record is authoritative, and the payload's closing NUL is a
consistency and resynchronization marker, not the framing.
.SH RECORD KINDS
.TP
.B stream-start
First record of every stream. Fields:
.B v
(format version, this document describes
.BR v=1 ),
.B from
/
.B to
(the selection window in Unix milliseconds; omitted edges are
unbounded),
.B has
(repeated; the chunk-level token requirements of the selection),
.B sources
(number of inputs). The selection echo lets a downstream tool record
the provenance of what it consumed.
.TP
.B source
One per input, in argument order, before any entries. Fields:
.B path
(the source as given),
.B kept
/
.B total
(chunks selected vs present \(em what the index did for this stream;
a consumer can warn \(lqthis will be slow\(rq before reading further).
.TP
.B entry
Announces the next record: its verbatim payload. Fields:
.B len
(payload length in bytes, authoritative),
.B ts
(the entry's own timestamp, Unix milliseconds; absent when the entry
carries no parseable stamp),
.B wf
/
.B wl
(first/last write time of the chunk the entry started in \(em the
write-time window),
.B src
(source path; present only in multi-source streams \(em single-source
streams name their source once, in
.BR stream-start / source ).
.TP
.B stream-end
Last record of every complete stream. Fields:
.B entries
(payloads emitted),
.B dropped
(entries verified outside the window),
.B chunks_read
/
.B chunks_total
(work done vs store size). Its PRESENCE is the completeness marker:
a consumer that reaches end-of-input without seeing
.B stream-end
must treat the stream as truncated (the producer died, or the pipe
broke) and must not present the result as complete.
.SH VERSIONING
The stream is versioned by the
.B v
field of
.BR stream-start .
Consumers MUST ignore unknown keys and unknown record kinds \(em new
fields and kinds may appear within
.B v=1
and are always additive. A consumer seeing a
.B v
it does not know should refuse rather than guess.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR timberfs (1)
